Cornwall, England":"Newlyn, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","St Michael Penkevil, Cornwall, England":"St Michael Penkivel, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Borlase","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English, Scottish: locative name from Old French  <i>bordelais</i> ‘man from Bordeaux’."],"variants":[{"name":"Borlace","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Borlase  ."]},{"name":"Barlas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Sajid, Ali, Humaira, Mohammed, Rehan.  Greek Dimitrios, Spiro, Spiros.","Scottish (Perthshire): habitational name, probably from Barloch, near Milngavie (Stirlings) + post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. The final syllable of <i>Barloch</i> will alternatively have been pronounced <i>-low</i> and <i>-lie</i> in Scots, whence a variety of attested surname forms including <i>Barlow</i>, <i>Barlows</i>, <i>Barlie</i>, <i>Barliss</i>, <i>Barles(s)</i>, and <i>Barlas(s)</i>, mostly clustering in settlements near Blackruthven in Tibbermore parish (Perthshire), where the surname <i>Barloche</i> is first recorded in 1589.","Greek: probably a nickname derived from <i>parla</i> ‘blabbering’ (from Italian <i>parlare</i> ‘to talk’). Alternatively, perhaps a nickname derived from Aromanian <i>bărliv</i> ‘tormented, long-suffering’."]},{"name":"Burlace","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Borlase  ."]},{"name":"Burles","meanings":["1  English: variant of   Burle   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>.","2  Norman, English:  see  Borlase  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":13,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John Borlase was born in 1442, in Cornwall, England, his father, John Borlase, was 23 and his mother, Sophia Elizabeth Trevener, was 25. He married Margaret Kingdon in 1474, in Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1511, in Newlyn, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1442–1511":"1442–1511","1449–1519":"1449–1519","1482–Male":"1482–Surnud","1500–1544":"1500–1544","1420–1472":"1420–1472","1418–1539":"1418–1539","1472":"1472","1482":"1482","1500":"1500","1511":"1511","1544":"1544","1455":"1455","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","1519":"1519","1539":"1539","1418":"1418","1449":"1449","Borlase, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Borlase Hall, Newlyn,  Cornwall, England":"Newlyn, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","St Michael Penkevil, Cornwall, England":"St Michael Penkivel, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1442–1511":"1442–1511","1449–1519":"1449–1519","1482–Male":"1482–Kuollut","1500–1544":"1500–1544","1420–1472":"1420–1472","1418–1539":"1418–1539","1472":"1472","1482":"1482","1500":"1500","1511":"1511","1544":"1544","1455":"1455","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","1519":"1519","1539":"1539","1418":"1418","1449":"1449","Borlase, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Borlase Hall, Newlyn,  Cornwall, England":"Newlyn, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kun